04560nam a22005535i 9780822398370DE-B159720210106113355.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210106t20002000ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223983707 a10.1515/97808223983702doi  a(DE-B1597)552710  a(OCoLC)972005000  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aD802.F8bK65 1999 7aHIS0130002bisacsh04a944.0821 aKoreman, Megan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Expectation of Justice :bFrance, 1944-1946 /cMegan Koreman. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2000] 4c©2000  a1 online resource (368 p.) :b6 b&w photographs, 7 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tMaps -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tCHAPTER I. Three Towns, Three Liberations -- tCHAPTER 2. Living in the Aftermath of War -- tCHAPTER 3. Legal Justice and the Purge of Collaborators -- tCHAPTER 4. Social Justice and the Provisioning Crisis -- tCHAPTER 5. Honorary Justice and the Construction of Memory -- tCHAPTER 6. Popular Justice or Republican Legitimacy? -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn The Expectation of Justice Megan Koreman traces the experiences of three small French towns during the troubled months of the Provisional Government following the Liberation in 1944. Her descriptions of the towns' different wartime and postwar experiences contribute to a fresh depiction of mid-century France and illustrate the failure of the postwar government to adequately serve the interests of justice.As the first social history of the "après -Libération" period from the perspective of ordinary people, Koreman's study reveals how citizens of these towns expected legal, social, and honorary justice-such as punishment for collaborators, fair food distribution, and formal commemoration of patriots, both living and dead. Although the French expected the Resistance's Provisional Government to act according to local understandings of justice, its policies often violated local sensibilities by instead pursuing national considerations. Koreman assesses both the citizens' eventual disillusionment and the social costs of the "Resistencialist myth" propagated by the de Gaulle government in an effort to hold together the fragmented postwar nation. She also suggests that the local demands for justice created by World War II were stifled by the Cold War, since many people in France feared that open opposition to the government would lead to a Communist takeover. This pattern of nationally instituted denial and suppression made it difficult for citizens to deal effectively with memories of wartime suffering and collaborationist betrayal. Now, with the end of the Cold War, says Koreman, memories of postwar injustices are resurfacing, and there is renewed interest in witnessing just and deserved closure.This social history of memory and reconstruction will engage those interested in history, war and peace issues, contemporary Europe, and the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Jan 2021) 0aSocial justicezFrancexHistoryvCase studies. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xCollaborationistszFrancevCase studies. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945zFrance. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822398370zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822398370423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822398370.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL